COURSERA GOOGLE LEARNING WITH PALMER PENGUINS

This exercise asks a basic question: Is there a causal relationship between body size and flipper length?

More specifically, our question is: how well does body size predict flipper length?

**Independent Variable: Body Size

Dependent Variable: Flipper Length**

Step 2 is loading data as a Tibble and doing Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA).

First, we load/import the dataset(s) and convert to a Tibble using as_tibble().

Second, we look at its overall structure and properties.

We use dim to see how many rows and columns we have, followed by str to provide a high level explanation of each columns data type. Then we use glimpse to preview the actual values in each row. Then we use summary to get basic descriptive statistics and view to open a new tab to look at the Tibble column by column.

EDA: First, lets drop the few NA values we have, and then check distribution and central tendency.

dataTIB <- na.omit(importTIB)

Now that we have cleaner data, we pull up histograms of our two variables so see if they have roughly normal distributions.

We can see that penguin body mass has a distribution that skews slightly right, pulled upwards by a few heavier outliers.

We also see that penguin bill length has an almost bi-modal distribution. Despite this, both have a mean and a median that are close together.

summary(dataTIB$bill_length_mm)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   32.10   39.50   44.50   43.99   48.60   59.60
hist(dataTIB$bill_length_mm) 

summary(dataTIB$body_mass_g)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    2700    3550    4050    4207    4775    6300
hist(dataTIB$body_mass_g)

More EDA: checking the dispersion of two related variables

We also want to look at the datas dispersion, looking at min and max values, plus the range and IQR for Inter-Quartile Range (IQR), plus the tried and true standard measure of dispersion, the Standard Deviation or SD. We also use the Plot function which will visualize the central tendency and dispersion in a violin plot that visualizes the interquartile range. This will let us get an understanding of the data that goes deeper than just the basic histogram or box-and-whisker plot.

min(dataTIB$bill_length_mm, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 32.1
max(dataTIB$bill_length_mm, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 59.6
range(dataTIB$bill_length_mm, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 32.1 59.6
IQR(dataTIB$bill_length_mm, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 9.1
sd(dataTIB$bill_length_mm, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 5.468668

Step 3: Hypothesizing a model

So we can see that our two variables are not very normally distributed, nor do they have low dispersion - not a great sign for using a standard linear model regression. But, since this is just to learn, lets see if we can find a line of best fit with these two. Again, our question is: how well does body size predict flipper length?

**Independent Variable: Body Size

Dependent Variable: Flipper Length**

So now lets plot these two variables and see what sort of relationship they might have.

ggplot(dataTIB, aes(body_mass_g, flipper_length_mm)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Body mass by flipper length") + 
  theme_bw()

Hypothesizing a model: an apparent linear relationship

We can now plot a line of best fit using geom_smooth(method = lm). As it shows, there is a fairly direct relationship between the penguins body mass and flipper length, overall, without considering the impact of some of the other possible causal variables.

ggplot(dataTIB, aes(body_mass_g, flipper_length_mm)) + 
    geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
    geom_smooth(method = lm, na.rm = TRUE) + 
    labs(title = "Body mass by flipper length") + 
    theme_bw()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

We know that there are three other variables in this dataset that might cause, or at least impact, flipper length. * Biological Sex * Penguin Species * Island Location

Adding the facet_wrap() argument within the ggplot function, we can do a side-by-side of our mass-length proposed model to see if any of these other variables seriously disrupt that model. As the below indicate, the mass-length relationship remains quite clear even when looking at it based on these other three variables.

ggplot(dataTIB, aes(body_mass_g, flipper_length_mm)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Body mass by flipper length, and by biological sex") + 
  theme_bw() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, na.rm = TRUE)+
  facet_wrap(~sex)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(dataTIB, aes(body_mass_g, flipper_length_mm)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Body mass by flipper length, and by species") + 
  theme_bw() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, na.rm = TRUE)+
  facet_wrap(~species)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(dataTIB, aes(body_mass_g, flipper_length_mm)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Body mass by flipper length, and by island") + 
  theme_bw() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, na.rm = TRUE)+
  facet_wrap(~island)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Step 4: Running regressions (simple linear bivariate)

Visuals with a line of best fit give an intuitive, overall explanation of the positive, probably causal relationship between the causal/independent variable and the dependent variable. We should also run a regression and look at its output to confirm the magnitude of the relationship. We want to see an R-squared (R^2) values close to 1, and a P-value close to 0. This is just going more mathematically in-depth to the linear model (lm) we inserted into the visuals above.

bivariate.regression <- lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = dataTIB)
summary(bivariate.regression)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = dataTIB)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -23.698  -4.983   1.056   5.101  13.933 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                Estimate  Std. Error t value            Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 137.0396209   1.9987694   68.56 <0.0000000000000002 ***
## body_mass_g   0.0151953   0.0004667   32.56 <0.0000000000000002 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 6.847 on 331 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7621, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7614 
## F-statistic:  1060 on 1 and 331 DF,  p-value: < 0.00000000000000022

We can see that R^2 is about 0.76, which is not as close to 1 as wed like, but is still a fairly strong linear relationship.

Additionally, the P-value is effectively zero, which means that there is a probability of 99.9999% of predicting the dependent variable using this model.

Running regressions (multi-variate, controlling for other variables)

Finally, lets see if our probably causal variable is still reliable at predicting the dependent variable when we factor in other possibly causal / confounding variables.

multivariate.regression <- lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g + sex + island + species, data = dataTIB) 
summary(multivariate.regression) 
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g + sex + island + 
##     species, data = dataTIB)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -14.4515  -3.1756  -0.0639   3.1517  15.2879 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                    Estimate Std. Error t value             Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)      163.308460   3.236687  50.455 < 0.0000000000000002 ***
## body_mass_g        0.006534   0.000925   7.064     0.00000000000986 ***
## sexmale            2.498202   0.848734   2.943              0.00348 ** 
## islandDream        1.163307   1.074299   1.083              0.27967    
## islandTorgersen    2.770541   1.114126   2.487              0.01339 *  
## speciesChinstrap   5.711688   0.963798   5.926     0.00000000788397 ***
## speciesGentoo     19.373659   1.579314  12.267 < 0.0000000000000002 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.311 on 326 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.859,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.8564 
## F-statistic:   331 on 6 and 326 DF,  p-value: < 0.00000000000000022

Good news!

We can see that R^2 is actually higher and closer to 1, at 0.859, reinforcing that there is strong, linear, probably causal relationship.

Additionally, the P-value is effectively zero for all the other variables (except for Dream Island), which means that there is a probability of 99.9999% of predicting the dependent variable using this model.

CONCLUSIONS AND NEXT STEPS

BODY MASS IS A GOOD PREDICTOR OF FLIPPER LENGTH

This data shows that overall, even when controlling for other possibly causal variables, body mass is a reliable predictor of flipper length.

There are a few other questions to think about that might be good next steps.

    1. Is the inverse true: is there a causal relationship between flipper length and body mass?
    1. What about sex or bill depth: do either of those cause larger body mass, or larger flipper length?
    1. Which of these causal relationships is the strongest and most reliable predictor?
